truth is that starting at a very low level (around 20), all NPC casters continue to ramp their melee skills, while PC casters fall off quickly.  The last time I remember fighting a true wizard classed mob (offense is all magic, but low defense and hitpoints) was the Erudites at a Dervish Cutthroat camp, or maybe the bats in the warrens.<br>
<br>
The truth is, that at a very low level, arcane combat just ceases to be a primary form of battle, and so offensive spellcasting becomes a support function.  I would stop short of calling this a fundamental design flaw, but it is a very deep seeded aspect of the EQ game design.  The exception is kiting, where wizards and druids use the game mechanics to their advantage to defeat a warrior classed mob by doing damage at a distance (a tactic which goes against a good part of the EQ design -- see many threads on archery for discussion of this).<br>
<br>
If Verant were to add &quot;melee-proof&quot; mobs, they should also make their melee attacks as weak as their melee defense is strong.  That would create a true arcane classed enemy that required those with arcane skills (wizards, among others) to defeat.<br>
<br>
- Armok Komra <br>
